&gt; I have no idea what was going on. I am guessing that Armadillo does things differently. But I can&#39;t find any sources to help me clear things out.

The ultimate source here is [the Armadillo docs](http://arma.sourceforge.net/docs.html). If you go down to [the section on operators](http://arma.sourceforge.net/docs.html#operators), you&#39;ll see that the `&amp;` operator is not one of those listed among the &quot;[o]verloaded operators for *Mat, Col, Row* and *Cube* classes.&quot; So, if you want such an operator you&#39;ll have to code it up yourself (or see if someone else already has it floating around the internet). There is such an operator for `Rcpp::NumericVector`s:

&lt;!-- language: lang-cpp --&gt;

    #include &lt;Rcpp.h&gt;
    
    // [[Rcpp::export]]
    Rcpp::LogicalVector test1(const Rcpp::NumericVector&amp; t1, double R1, double R2){
        return (t1 &gt;= R1) &amp; (t1 &lt; R2);
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-r --&gt;

    test1(1:10, 3, 7)
    # [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
    # [9] FALSE FALSE

Of course, that doesn&#39;t help much if the rest of your code really relies on Armadillo.

# Update: Just Use `&amp;&amp;`

As pointed out by [mtall](https://stackoverflow.com/users/1080929/mtall) in the comments, the `&amp;&amp;` operator actually **is** available, even though it&#39;s not discussed in the Armadillo docs (maybe it&#39;s not as ultimate of a source as I thought).

So, just change your code to the following:

&lt;!-- language: lang-cpp --&gt;

    #include &lt;RcppArmadillo.h&gt;
    // [[Rcpp::depends(RcppArmadillo)]]
    
    //[[Rcpp::export]]
    arma::uvec test1(arma::vec t1, double R1, double R2){
        arma::uvec t = (t1 &gt;= R1) &amp;&amp; (t1 &lt; R2);
        return t;
    }

and it works how I believe you want it to based on your question and response to comments:

&lt;!-- language: lang-r --&gt;

    test1(1:10, 3, 7)
          [,1]
     [1,]    0
     [2,]    0
     [3,]    1
     [4,]    1
     [5,]    1
     [6,]    1
     [7,]    0
     [8,]    0
     [9,]    0
    [10,]    0

